<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="450" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1807,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
We propose a subdivision of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1963" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1963" box="[658,951,1807,1833]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Arctoseiinae">
Arctoseiinae 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, G. O." box="[810,951,1807,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="275 - 303" refId="ref9978" refString="Evans, G. O. (1963) Observations on the chaetotaxy of the legs in the free-living Gamasina. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 10, 275 - 303. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 20528" type="journal article" year="1963">Evans, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
into three tribes, 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1963" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1963" box="[1160,1436,1807,1833]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctoseiini">
Arctoseiini 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, G. O." box="[1294,1436,1807,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="275 - 303" refId="ref9978" refString="Evans, G. O. (1963) Observations on the chaetotaxy of the legs in the free-living Gamasina. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 10, 275 - 303. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 20528" type="journal article" year="1963">Evans, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(numbering about 60 species), 
<taxonomicName authority="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist, 2021" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[497,645,1843,1869]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Zerconopsini">Zerconopsini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[652,739,1842,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" rank="tribe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[652,732,1842,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">tribe n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(about 25 species), and monobasic 
<taxonomicName authority="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist, 2021" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[1140,1250,1843,1869]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Maxiniini">Maxiniini</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1257,1344,1842,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1257,1344,1842,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" rank="tribe">tribe n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1807,2013]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,645]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="450" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
The strongly evident relationship of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gwiazdovicz" authorityYear="2004" box="[598,743,1879,1905]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Iphidonopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[598,743,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Iphidonopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1918" box="[755,891,1879,1904]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Zerconopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[755,891,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Zerconopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindquist &amp; Evans" authorityYear="1965" box="[949,1063,1879,1904]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Xenoseius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[949,1063,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Xenoseius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on apomorphic attributes (dorsoproximal setae 
<emphasis box="[393,421,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">ad</emphasis>
-2 and 
<emphasis box="[498,526,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">pd</emphasis>
-2 of tarsi II to IV elongated, curved, somewhat whip-like; hypostomal setae 
<emphasis box="[1385,1413,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">hp</emphasis>
-1 and to some extent 
<emphasis box="[373,401,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">hp</emphasis>
-3, as well as the internal palp trochanter seta elongated, whip-like) and on a plesiomorphic attribute (genu III with eight setae, including 
<emphasis box="[673,699,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">pv</emphasis>
-1). Besides, females of these genera possess an often expansive ventrianal shield usually bearing one to six pairs of opisthogastric setae in addition to the circumanal setae (female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gwiazdovicz" authorityYear="2004" box="[151,296,187,213]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Iphidonopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">Iphidonopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exceptional, having a large anal shield bearing only the circumanal setae) along with one or two pairs of free metapodal platelets. All these characteristics argue for the deriving of a tribe 
<taxonomicName authority="Segregation" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[1089,1237,223,249]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Zerconopsini">Zerconopsini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1243,1330,222,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" rank="tribe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1243,1323,222,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">tribe n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
Segregation of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1963" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1963" box="[332,602,259,285]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctoseiini">
Arctoseiini 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, G. O." box="[463,602,259,285]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" pagination="275 - 303" refId="ref9978" refString="Evans, G. O. (1963) Observations on the chaetotaxy of the legs in the free-living Gamasina. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 10, 275 - 303. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 20528" type="journal article" year="1963">Evans, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thor" authorityYear="1930" box="[731,848,259,285]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Arctoseius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[731,848,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">Arctoseius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1903" box="[903,1050,259,285]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" genus="Iphidozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[903,1050,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">Iphidozercon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is supported by such apomorphic attributes as reduced ventral sclerotisation (epigynal shield slender, anal shield bearing only three circumanal setae, sternal shield sometimes separated from endocoxal sclerites) and genu III with seven setae, lacking 
<emphasis box="[1270,1296,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">pv</emphasis>
-1. Recognition of the monobasic 
<taxonomicName authority="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist, 2021" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[407,517,367,393]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Maxiniini">Maxiniini</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[525,614,366,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[525,614,366,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" rank="tribe">tribe n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is strongly based apomorphically on a narrowed deutosternum, a highly expanded ventrianal shield incorporating metapodal platelets and bearing setae 
<emphasis box="[1034,1064,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">JV</emphasis>
1, along with the absence of setae 
<emphasis box="[151,184,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">ZV</emphasis>
<quantity box="[184,227,439,465]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
both sexes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450">
Although the single known species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist, 2021" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[639,749,475,501]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Maxiniini">Maxiniini</taxonomicName>
seems to be free-living in soil litter throughout all its broad range (
<bibRefCitation author="Lindquist, E. E. &amp; Makarova, O. L." box="[229,564,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref10527" refString="Lindquist, E. E. &amp; Makarova, O. L. (2012) Review of the mite subfamily Arctoseiinae Evans with a key to its genera and description of a new genus and species from Siberia (Parasitiformes, Mesostigmata, Ascidae). ZooKeys, 233, 1 - 20. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 233.3862" type="journal article" year="2012">Lindquist &amp; Makarova, 2012</bibRefCitation>
), numerous members of the two other tribes display some clear tendencies in their ecological specialisation associated phoretically with winged dipterans, namely an inclination to fungal substrata in 
<taxonomicName authority="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist, 2021" authorityName="Makarova &amp; Marchenko &amp; Lindquist" authorityYear="2021" box="[249,397,583,609]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribe n." tribe="Zerconopsini">Zerconopsini</taxonomicName>
and to different wet habitats enriched by nematoceran juveniles (eggs, early stage larvae) in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1963" box="[151,279,619,645]" class="Arachnida" family="Ascidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="2" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctoseiini">Arctoseiini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
